{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583672"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:24:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:24:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12294"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12294","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12294"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.72,0.09,0.13,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4816"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77828"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4816","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4816"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12294"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63350"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3000"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"6087"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7728"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7737"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26743"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77828","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77828"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old patient attends his follow-up in the orthopaedic clinic following a recent open reduction and internal fixation following a fracture of the neck of his right humerus. He complains of weakness in lifting the affected arm and upon physical examination there is altered sensation over the lower aspect of the right deltoid.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following is most likely to have been damaged?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Median nerve","Axillary nerve","Musculocutaneous nerve","Radial nerve","Lateral cutaneous nerve"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient in the above stem has an apparent injury to his \u003Cstrong\u003Eaxillary nerve. \u003C/strong\u003EThe axillary nerve arises from the posterior cord of the brachial plexus and carries nerve fibres from C5 and C6, providing sensory innervation to the lower aspect of the deltoid region and motor innervation to the deltoid muscle and teres minor. Deltoid muscle weakness limits abduction of the affected arm beyond approximately 30 degrees, with this initial movement under the responsibility of the supraspinatus muscle. Further movement beyond 30 degrees of abduction is due to the contraction of the deltoid muscle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe median nerve\u003C/strong\u003E supplies motor innervation to the pronator teres and flexors of the wrist (not including the flexor carpi ulnaris and part of flexor digitorum profundus). Therefore injury to the median nerve results in may result in weakness of wrist flexion as well as pronation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMusculocutaneous nerve\u003C/strong\u003E damage/injury can results in weakness of forearm flexion (due to it providing motor innervation to the biceps brachii, coracobrachialis and brachialis). Injury may also result in altered/loss of sensation to the lateral aspect of the forearm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eradial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E provides motor innervation to the extensor compartments of the upper limb and thus injury to this nerve may result in weakness of extension at the elbow and wrist.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELateral cutaneous nerve of forearm\u003C/strong\u003E originates from spinal nerves C5-C7. It is the termination of musculocutaneous nerve. There is no motor innervation; it is pure sensory nerve.\u00a0Sensory innervation is to skin of lower anterolateral arm.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The axillary nerve provides motor innervation to the deltoid muscle and sensory innervation to the lower region of the deltoid.","Injury to the axillary nerve can occur with fractures of the surgical neck of the humerus, leading to deltoid weakness and sensory loss over the lateral shoulder."],"references":["Thatte MR, Babhulkar S, Hiremath A. Brachial plexus injury in adults: Diagnosis and surgical treatment strategies. Ann Indian Acad Neurol. 2013 Jan;16(1):26-33. doi: 10.4103/0972-2327.107686. PMID: 23661959; PMCID: PMC3644778. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3644778/","Kostretzis L, Theodoroudis I, Boutsiadis A, Papadakis N, Papadopoulos P. Suprascapular Nerve Pathology: A Review of the Literature. Open Orthop J. 2017 Feb 28;11:140-153. doi: 10.2174/1874325001711010140. PMID: 28400882; PMCID: PMC5366386. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28400882/","Tessler J, Talati R. Axillary Nerve Injury. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK539895/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63350"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12294"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63350","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63350"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T13:00:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T13:01:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4816"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77828"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/